What i notice a lot is the question "Will AI replace the jobs?", and the answer to that is... not really. What people dont see is that AI can be the best assist tool for the jobs (or practically anything). Humans have the weakness of making mathematical errors and having limited speed of work process. Meanwhile AI has exactly that advantage, but has a weakness of lack of understanding context (and some other errors/flaws), which, you guessed it, is where humans have the advantage. 

Both have the advantage where other has weakness, which is exactly why having a human work along with AI is the potential used to its fullest. The virtually unstoppable duo with possibly no weaknesses if working together.

Hell, lets even go to the currently controversial topic of AI art. People treat it as stolen work that has no soul, but dont realize that the AI generated images work as the perfect template/reference/inspiration for the artist to create something. This is also the example of AI and person covering each other's weaknesses, since AI can generate the image that looks extremely good and shows creativity, but it lacks understanding of detail (as seen if you zoom the images on certain objects), which again, is where humans have strength. 

The main problem here is people completely misunderstanding this new technology that they dont see the potential within it just because they watched too many science fiction movies. I personally cant wait what future holds for us, but one thing is for sure: AI is the future

Yes it's clear that chat GPT will help you with simple stuff along the way, but I'd be far more curious to see it build a MERN stack app that implements a REST API. Things like that become FAR more complex and I doubt it will be able to track issues or give useful information on bugs. What you demonstrated here is what I would consider to be the equivalent in knowledge to a month long "Learn to Web Dev from scratch" scam class. It'll teach the absolute basics to HTML, CSS, and JS and develop a shitty website to be proud of but create zero actual usable experience. Your CSS isn't even using selectors that aren't elements... You're putting a fetch in client side JS and even storing in a database... For those not devs here this is a HUGE no no. Client side JS can be altered in the inspect view of your browser. not to mention the .json file is downloaded to the client when they visit the website...

 Lastly Hostinger is not the best web host out there especially since AWS ec2 can host completely free for a year and dollars after that. You can also get SSL free through let's encrypt and Domains are fairly cheap, not to mention many have free trial options. To be clear there are lots of free options people. Don't pay a dollar if you're just starting out.

Also Cute locking your classes behind a pay wall. For those reading the comments if you want to learn algos check our HackerRank. They make great vids on topics and have a fully interactive environment for you to practice in all without the $49 pay wall. Also these are popular topics for devs so you'll most likely find PLENTY of free alternatives.

Point being, the information here is misleading at best. Chat GPT won't be taking dev jobs for a while. It does things in the simplest possible manner at the moment, it can optimize but cant debug.

First of all, Chat GPT is fed answers from data which is generated by regular people, which as we know are prone to making mistakes, and so you can see how Chat GPT will also serve you plain wrong answers. Other than serving you wrong or outdated information, it doesn' have the capacity to adjust to your specific needs, it may provide you with a code snippet, but how that code snippet will fit in with the rest of the code, that's for the programmer to understand and work around.

Essentially, Chat GPT is contextually a better search engine for programmers, nothing more. And I want to emphasize contextually, because it's not even a replacement for Google. I've been using Chat GPT a lot lately, and it is an incredible tool that saves a lot of my time, but let me tell you this as someone in computer science, you do not want to blindly copy-paste the answers Chat GPT provides. Even if it spits out working code, in computer science it's not enough to just make a working code, it's also important to observe how scalable this code is and whether it fits your needs.

Long story short, at best script kiddies should be worried, but software engineers have nothing to worry about, in fact they welcome it, makes their lives easier. The more code you type you'll see how lazy you get to re-type some mundane stuff so you usually just Google it every time and copy-paste, readjust for your project.

I've been using it a lot for the past three weeks. It's pretty incredible. I'm mid thirties, but started coding when I was 11 and sold my first website at 13 to a gaming company. Back then, it was a lot of html/css/php/etc. There weren't nearly as many microservices and overall architectures weren't nearly as fragmented as they are now - which is something that ChatGPT can help with but cannot yet fully alleviate. 
In it's current state, it works well and can give fairly accurate coding docs for more basic/simple exercises most of the time. But it struggles with any sort of complex hierarchies and sometimes even basic functions.

That said, the tech is only going to get better and that's both exciting and scary. 

Funny side note, my wife is a professor in a STEM field and she was dreading having to write tests/quizzes (her least favorite part). So, we went to ChatGPT and were blown away! It was arguably much better writing quizzes and exams than it was writing code. Not only that, but we were able to access material behind paywalls/subscriptions that we shouldn't have. In just a couple of days we wrote all of her quizzes and tests, recommendation letters for students, and various correspondences. Of course, things were later personalized and we had to verify the accuracy of it but at the end of the day it was roughly 90-95% accurate/correct for her work, and I found around 75-80% for more simpler versions of my software engineering work. It was also useful in some instances of DS applications (DNN's/GANS mostly), system designs and services architecture - just not accurate enough to be trusted without verification.

All in all, it is currently a helpful tool to add to the toolkit for most engineers I should think!

It's unlikely that GPT-4 or any other language model will fully replace developers, as there are many tasks that require human creativity, problem-solving, and expertise. However, GPT-4 and other language models can certainly assist developers in a number of ways, such as by automatically generating code snippets, documentation, or even entire programs. They can also help with tasks such as natural language understanding, natural language generation, and machine translation.

One example is using GPT-4 as a code snippet generator to help developers write code quickly and efficiently. GPT-4 can be trained on a dataset of code snippets, and then be used to generate new code snippets that match a given input or prompt. This can save developers a lot of time and effort when working on a project, especially for repetitive tasks such as writing boilerplate code.

Additionally, with natural language understanding, GPT-4 can automatically parse and understand the intent of the customerâ€™s requirements. That will help developers to understand the requirements more clearly and write the correct code.

However, while language models like GPT-4 can certainly be useful tools for developers, they still require human oversight and expertise to ensure that the code they generate is correct, efficient, and secure. Additionally, GPT-4 isn't even built yet, GPT-3 is currently the latest one.
